        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Core concepts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "preregistration",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Preregistration"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nupvzyrfo6l",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Preregistration refers to archiving a research plan (e.g., aims/hypotheses, methods, and analyses) in a public registry, typically before any data has been collected. Preregistration is intended to reduce the risk of bias by encouraging researchers to make decisions independently of the data ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "niz1dx66d7r",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nkikp8lixys\" data-reactroot=\"\">Hardwicke, T. E., &amp; Wagenmakers, E.-J. (2023). Reducing bias, increasing transparency and calibrating confidence with preregistration. <em>Nature Human Behaviour</em>, <em>7</em>(1), 15\u201326. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1038/s41562-022-01497-2\">https://doi.org/10.1038/s41562-022-01497-2</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Hardwicke & Wagenmakers, 2023",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). When research decisions such as how to define outliers are made with knowledge of the data, those decisions can be skewed in favor of the researchers\u2019 preferred outcome, creating a risk of bias. A public preregistration also enables readers to identify which decisions were preplanned (decreasing the risk of bias) and which were not (increasing the risk of bias) and appropriately calibrate their confidence in the study results. Preregistration templates have been developed for a variety of cognitive science domains, such as quantitative psychology ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nnqt96yb9o0",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n8lfkn1rgq2\" data-reactroot=\"\">Bosnjak, M., Fiebach, C. J., Mellor, D., Mueller, S., O\u2019Connor, D. B., Oswald, F. L., &amp; Sokol, R. I. (2022). A template for preregistration of quantitative research in psychology: Report of the joint psychological societies preregistration task force. <em>American Psychologist</em>, <em>77</em>(4), 602\u2013615. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1037/amp0000879\">https://doi.org/10.1037/amp0000879</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Bosnjak et al., 2022",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "), cognitive modeling ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nzm5q0t25ab",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n1vj038m1qf\" data-reactroot=\"\">Cr\u00fcwell, S., &amp; Evans, N. J. (2021). Preregistration in diverse contexts: A preregistration template for the application of cognitive models. <em>Royal Society Open Science</em>, <em>8</em>(10), 210155. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1098/rsos.210155\">https://doi.org/10.1098/rsos.210155</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Cr\u00fcwell & Evans, 2021",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "), and experimental linguistics ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nh8bmxw85no",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n9slem235ru\" data-reactroot=\"\">Roettger, T. B. (2021). Preregistration in experimental linguistics: Applications, challenges, and limitations. <em>Linguistics</em>, <em>59</em>(5), 1227\u20131249. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1515/ling-2019-0048\">https://doi.org/10.1515/ling-2019-0048</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Roettger, 2021",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") [see "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "link",
                "attrs": {
                  "href": "https://oecs.mit.edu/pub/lwxmte1p",
                  "title": null,
                  "target": null,
                  "pubEdgeId": null
                }
              }
            ],
            "text": "Bayesian Models of Cognition"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "]."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "open-data-materials-and-analysis-scripts",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Open data, materials, and analysis scripts"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "ncsqdzteyw0",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Sharing data can facilitate the detection of error or fraud, synthesis and aggregation of evidence, and novel discovery. Anonymization or other precautions are sometimes necessary to ensure data are shared responsibly ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n8r981oxt68",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n1p6p13bz5o\" data-reactroot=\"\">Meyer, M. N. (2018). Practical tips for ethical data sharing. <em>Advances in Methods and Practices in Psychological Science</em>, <em>1</em>(1), 131\u2013144. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1177/2515245917747656\">https://doi.org/10.1177/2515245917747656</a> </p>",
              "customLabel": "Meyer, 2018",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). Sharing materials such as stimuli, survey instruments, software, and detailed methods ensures that research can be thoroughly evaluated. It also increases efficiency by facilitating reuse and enables independent verification, for example, through replication studies. Sharing analysis scripts enables independent researchers to verify whether the reported results can be obtained by repeating the original analysis with the original data ("
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "computational reproducibility"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). Analysis scripts document how data were filtered, transformed, analyzed, and visualized, usually in computational code.\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "open-access",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Open access"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "\u00a0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "nvqaxs6w3d6",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Open access refers to making research articles freely available to readers. Traditionally, most scientific publications are only accessible to scientists based at institutions that can afford journal subscription fees. Open access advocates argue that this practice is unfair, as most research is funded by the public; moreover, making research accessible to all would maximize its benefits to society. Increasingly, researchers share preprints: freely accessible research articles stored on preprint servers such as "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "em"
              }
            ],
            "text": "PsyArXiv"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n84ipwsqdtl",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"ncgxxhdan0q\" data-reactroot=\"\">Moshontz, H., Binion, G., Walton, H., Brown, B. T., &amp; Syed, M. (2021). A guide to posting and managing preprints. <em>Advances in Methods and Practices in Psychological Science</em>, <em>4</em>(2). <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1177/25152459211019948\">https://doi.org/10.1177/25152459211019948</a> </p>",
              "customLabel": "Moshontz et al., 2021",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). Some journals also make some or all of their articles open access, although often the authors have to pay a fee."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "questions-controversies-and-new-developments",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "strong"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Questions, controversies, and new developments"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "attrs": {
          "id": "n8c8hjk3e0o",
          "class": null,
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
          "suggestionTimestamp": null,
          "suggestionUserId": null,
          "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
          "suggestionKind": null,
          "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Despite its scientific benefits, open science can increase pressures (e.g., workload or financial) on individual scientists, which may exacerbate existing inequalities ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nkf7c4ra7d7",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n3iluzg53av\" data-reactroot=\"\">Bahlai, C., Bartlett, L., Burgio, K., Fournier, A., Keiser, C., Poisot, T., &amp; Whitney, K. (2019). Open science isn\u2019t always open to all scientists. <em>American Scientist</em>, <em>107</em>(2), 78. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1511/2019.107.2.78\">https://doi.org/10.1511/2019.107.2.78</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Bahlai et al., 2019",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). Additionally, it is not always clear how to balance transparency with competing legal, ethical, or practical constraints. For example, it has been argued that open science could facilitate harassment in controversial areas such as climate science ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nkvwflrv2xp",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n4gv9vxxby7\" data-reactroot=\"\">Lewandowsky, S., &amp; Bishop, D. (2016). Don\u2019t let transparency damage science. <em>Nature</em>, <em>529</em>(7587), 459\u2013461. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1038/529459a\">https://doi.org/10.1038/529459a</a> </p>",
              "customLabel": "Lewandowsky & Bishop, 2016",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ") and create challenges for qualitative researchers ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "n5xml2i6d2t",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"n94epqww3zo\" data-reactroot=\"\">Pownall, M., Talbot, C. V., Kilby, L., &amp; Branney, P. (2023). Opportunities, challenges and tensions: Open science through a lens of qualitative social psychology. <em>British Journal of Social Psychology</em>, <em>62</em>(4), 1581\u20131589. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1111/bjso.12628\">https://doi.org/10.1111/bjso.12628</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Pownall et al., 2023",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "). As the adoption of open science practices has increased, a number of implementation problems have been surfaced by meta-research. For example, open datasets are often inadequately documented ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "nwleam94h35",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"ng1hhv5kf32\" data-reactroot=\"\">Towse, J. N., Ellis, D. A., &amp; Towse, A. S. (2020). Opening Pandora\u2019s Box: Peeking inside psychology\u2019s data sharing practices, and seven recommendations for change. <em>Behavior Research Methods</em>, <em>53</em>, 1455\u20131468. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.3758/s13428-020-01486-1\">https://doi.org/10.3758/s13428-020-01486-1</a> </p>",
              "customLabel": "Towse et al., 2020",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "), and researchers often fail to disclose deviations from preregistered plans ("
          },
          {
            "type": "citation",
            "attrs": {
              "id": "njhbumu37aw",
              "href": null,
              "value": "",
              "unstructuredValue": "<p id=\"nlxw4bo5apf\" data-reactroot=\"\">Claesen, A., Gomes, S., Tuerlinckx, F., &amp; Vanpaemel, W. (2021). Comparing dream to reality: An assessment of adherence of the first generation of preregistered studies. <em>Royal Society Open Science</em>, <em>8</em>(10), 211037. <a href=\"https://doi.org/10.1098/rsos.211037\">https://doi.org/10.1098/rsos.211037</a></p>",
              "customLabel": "Claesen et al., 2021",
              "suggestionId": null,
              "suggestionTimestamp": null,
              "suggestionUserId": null,
              "suggestionDiscussionId": null,
              "suggestionKind": null,
              "suggestionOriginalAttrs": null
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ")."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 1,
          "fixedId": "",
          "id": "broader-connections",
          "textAlign": null,
          "rtl": null,
          "suggestionId": null,
